    "143319012": {
      "title": "Sarantakos's Research on Same-Sex Parenting in Australia and New Zealand: Importance, Substance, and Corroboration with Research from the United States",
      "abstract": "Abstract Sarantakos (1996a) compared teacher ratings and other outcomes for the children of heterosexual married, heterosexual cohabiting, and homosexual parents and reported numerous significant, substantial differences. Few scholars have taken the effect sizes of his results into account or have considered his larger program of research. Sarantakos's research yielded many interesting findings with respect to children's academic performance, sexual orientation, use of alcohol and drugs, sexual deviance, and gender identity with respect to parents’ parenting values, relationship stability, conflict, monogamy, and religiosity or moral values, many of which have been corroborated by U.S. or British research. In addition, the methodological quality of his research appears to be at least above average, especially for research done 20 or more years ago. He appears to have been unbiased with respect to same-sex families. His results disseminated via multiple publications should be taken into account in literatu..."
    },
    "41479470": {
      "title": "Lesbian and Traditional Mothers' Responses to Adult Response to Child Behavior and Self-Concept",
      "abstract": "Summary.-A purposive sample of 34 lesbian and 47 traditional mothers was located in the Denver-Fort Collins area. This pilot study was designed to determi.ne if statistically significant differences existed between the two groups of morhers on measures of maternal attitude and self-concept. The Adult Response to Child Behavior, a set of slides of children's behaviors and set responses, provided an indicacor of adult-, task-, and child-centered attitudes. Three personality aggregates, self-confidence, dominance, and nurturance, were computed from responses to the Adjective Checklist, a 300-item self-administered, selfevaluative instrument. Chi-square analyses confirmed that: there is no difference in response to children's behavior by lesbian and traditional mothers nor in self-concept of lesbian and traditional mothers. This conclusion can be generalized only ro the subjects and instruments used in the present study. Further research is needed to provide a data base on interaction of lesbian mothers and children. It seems probable that lesbian and traditional mothers are more similar than different in maternal attitudes and self-concept. Educators are only now beginning to realize che complexity of parental behavior. Two recurring themes stand out in research on parents and children. The first theme is a positive correlation between a mother's and a child's selfconcepc (Gordon, 1976; Walters & Scinnett, 1971). The second describes child-rearing as a product of maternal attitudes, values, and personality characteristics (Heilbrun & Norbert, 1970; Hoffman, 1975; Sears, Maccoby, & Levin, 1957; Walters & Scinnett, 1971). A search for literature on lesbian mothers evidenced little information. Although the liceramre contains articles discussing parental attitudes which contributed to a person's becoming homosexual, there seem to be no data on what role is played by overt parental homosexualicy in a child's later becoming homosexual or developing emotional disturbance (Weeks, Deredyn, & Langman, 1975). In this pilot study self-concepts and maternal attitudes of lesbian and traditional mothers were compared. Responses to self-concept and maternalatcitude measures for these two groups were compared. This pilot study was designed to determine if there were statistically significant differences between the cwo groups of mothers on measures of maternal attitude and self-concept. A purposive sample of 34 lesbian and 47 traditional mothers was located in the Denver-Fort Collins area. For the purpose of this study, a lesbian mother was defined as one who was psychologically, emotionally, and sexually attracted and interested in other women and who, from a previous relationship with a man, had conceived a"
